🔐 Credential Management (Dev vs. Prod)
To ensure high security, never hardcode API keys or include raw JSON credential files in your Git repository. The SDKs are configured to find credentials automatically.

🟢 Google Cloud Storage (GCS)
This package uses Google's Application Default Credentials (ADC). It looks for credentials automatically without asking for file paths.

💻 In Local Development (Dev):
You do not need to generate a service account JSON file. Instead, use your own Google user permissions.

Install the Google Cloud CLI (gcloud).

Run the following command in your terminal:  gcloud auth application-default login

A browser will open. Log in with the Google account that has access to your GCP project. The SDK will automatically locate these locally generated credentials.

In Production (Prod):
Do not use gcloud auth.

Create a dedicated IAM Service Account in your GCP console and grant it the Storage Object Admin or Storage Object Viewer role.

Attach this Service Account directly to your computing resource (e.g., Cloud Run, Compute Engine, or GKE via Workload Identity).

The Go SDK will automatically detect the attached service account via the internal metadata server. No environment variables or files are required!



The AWS SDK v2 looks for credentials in standard AWS locations.

💻 In Local Development (Dev):
Install the AWS CLI.

Run aws configure and input your IAM User's Access Key and Secret Key.

The SDK will automatically read these keys from your default standard location (~/.aws/credentials).

☁️ In Production (Prod):
Never use access keys or secret keys on live servers.

If running on EC2, assign an IAM Role to the instance.

If running on ECS, use Task Roles.

If running on EKS, use IAM Roles for Service Accounts (IRSA).

The Go SDK will automatically detect and assume these roles natively without passing parameters in the code.


